    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. i also heard there's a difference between that and caramelization since they both cause browning. can you explain the main difference between the two so i don't mix them up on the test?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While both the Maillard reaction and caramelization result in browning, they occur at different temperature ranges and involve different types of reactions. The Maillard reaction is a general term for the non-enzymatic browning of foods, while caramelization is a specific type of Maillard reaction that occurs when starches and sugars are heated to extremely high temperatures, typically above 338°C (640°F).\n\nIn caramelization, the focus is on the breakdown of sugars to form new compounds with distinct flavors and aromas, often resulting in a rich, sweet flavor. In contrast, the Maillard reaction is a broader process that can occur at lower temperatures and involves the interaction of amino acids and reducing sugars, resulting in a more complex flavor profile.",
